 function, or real linear functional), then formula_237 is continuous at the origin if and only if formula_237 is uniformly continuous on all of formula_11; and if in addition formula_240 then formula_237 is continuous if and only if its absolute value formula_242 is continuous, which happens if and only if formula_243 is an open subset of formula_140 \nAnd very importantly for applying the Hahn\u2013Banach theorem, a linear functional formula_237 is continuous if and only if this is true of its real part formula_246 and moreover, formula_247 and the real part formula_246 completely determines formula_249 which is why the Hahn\u2013Banach theorem is often stated only for real linear functionals.\nAlso, a linear functional formula_237 on formula_11 is continuous if and only if the seminorm formula_252 is continuous, which happens if and only if there exists a continuous seminorm formula_253 such that formula_254; this last statement involving the linear functional formula_237 and seminorm formula_256 is encountered in many versions of the Hahn\u2013Banach theorem.\nBasic notions.\nThe Cartesian product formula_257 of two normed spaces is not canonically equipped with a norm. However, several equivalent norms are commonly used, such as\nformula_258\nwhich correspond (respectively) to the coproduct and product in the category of Banach spaces and short maps (discussed above). For finite (co)products, these norms give rise to isomorphic normed spaces, and the product formula_257 (or the direct sum formula_260) is complete if and only if the two factors are complete.\nIf formula_261 is a closed linear subspace of a normed space formula_155 there is a natural norm on the quotient space formula_263\nformula_264\nThe quotient formula_265 is a Banach space when formula_11 is complete. The quotient map from formula_11 onto formula_263 sending formula_269 to its class formula_270 is linear, onto and has norm formula_271 except when formula_272 in which case the quotient is the