ended for example to the case where formula_11 is a Fr\u00e9chet space, provided the conclusion is modified as follows: under the same hypothesis, there exists a neighborhood formula_506 of formula_363 in formula_11 such that all formula_185 in formula_510 are uniformly bounded on formula_511\nformula_512\nThis result is a direct consequence of the preceding \"Banach isomorphism theorem\" and of the canonical factorization of bounded linear maps.\nThis is another consequence of Banach's isomorphism theorem, applied to the continuous bijection from formula_513 onto formula_11 sending formula_515 to the sum formula_516\nReflexivity.\nThe normed space formula_11 is called reflexive when the natural map\nformula_518\nis surjective. Reflexive normed spaces are Banach spaces.\nThis is a consequence of the Hahn\u2013Banach theorem. \nFurther, by the open mapping theorem, if there is a bounded linear operator from the Banach space formula_11 onto the Banach space formula_520 then formula_183 is reflexive.\nIndeed, if the dual formula_522 of a Banach space formula_183 is separable, then formula_183 is separable. \nIf formula_11 is reflexive and separable, then the dual of formula_178 is separable, so formula_178 is separable.\nHilbert spaces are reflexive. The formula_295 spaces are reflexive when formula_529 More generally, uniformly convex spaces are reflexive, by the Milman\u2013Pettis theorem. \nThe spaces formula_530 are not reflexive. \nIn these examples of non-reflexive spaces formula_155 the bidual formula_465 is \"much larger\" than formula_140 \nNamely, under the natural isometric embedding of formula_11 into formula_465 given by the Hahn\u2013Banach theorem, the quotient formula_536 is infinite-dimensional, and even nonseparable. \nHowever, Robert C. James has constructed an example of a non-reflexive space, usually called \"the James space\" and denoted by formula_537 such that the quotient formula_538 is one-dimensional. \nFurthermore, this space formula_539 is isometrically isomorphic to its bidual.\nWhen formula_11 is reflexive, it follows that all closed and bounded convex subsets of formula_11 are weakly compact. \nIn a Hilbert space formula_428 the weak compactness of the unit ball is very often used in the following way: every bounded sequence in formula_310 has weakly convergent subsequences.\nWeak compactness of the unit ball provides a tool for finding solutions in reflexive spaces to certain optimization problems. \nFor example, every convex continuous function on the unit ball formula_544 of a reflexive space attains its minimum at some point in formula_545\nAs a special case of the preceding result, when formula_11 is a reflexive space over formula_547 every continuous linear functional formula_237 in formula_178 attains its maximum formula_550 on the unit ball of formula_140 \nThe following theorem of Robert C. James provides a converse statement.\nThe theorem can be extended to give a characterization of weakly compact convex sets.\nOn every non-reflexive Banach space formula_155 there exist continuous linear functionals that are not \"norm-attaining\". \nHowever, the Bishop\u2013Phelps theorem states that norm-attaining functionals are norm dense in the dual formula_178 of formula_140\nWeak convergences of sequences.\nA sequence formula_555 in a Banach space formula_11 is weakly convergent to a vector formula_269 if formula_558 converges to formula_559 for every continuous linear functional formula_237 in the dual formula_561 The sequence formula_555 is a weakly Cauchy sequence if formula_558 converges to a scalar limit formula_564 for every formula_237 in formula_561 \nA sequence formula_567 in the dual formula_178 is weakly* convergent to a functional formula_569 if formula_570 converges to formula_559 for every formula_28 in formula_140 \nWeakly Cauchy sequences, weakly convergent and weakly* convergent sequences are norm bounded, as a consequence of the Banach\u2013Steinhaus theorem.\nWhen the sequence f